<a href="javascript:card_browser(24)">Lurtz, Servant of Isengard</a> X2<br>
Ulaire Cantea, LODG X2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(855)">Savagery to Match Their Numbers</a> X4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(31)">Saruman&#39;s Ambition</a> X4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(19)">Bred for Battle</a> X2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(25)">Lurtz&#39;s Battle Cry</a> X2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(953)">Wizard Storm</a> X2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(944)">Beyond the Height of Men</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(36)">Spies of Saruman</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(843)">The Balrog, Durin&#39;s Bane</a><br>
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> There is a ton of strategy, so make sure you read it all.  You just might learn something...<br>
<br>
The fellowship side focuses on Galdalf and lots of companions to survive and Uruks to kill stuff.  I took this deck to the Washington TOC, and it finished with a 4-2 record.  Most of the games that I won was with my shadow side, possibly because of me finally owning 4 savageries.<br>
<br>
During the tournament I played against all of the shadow cultures and did very well.  The only reason I lost against the Nazgul game was because of a stupid mistake of mine (death at site 3 with an unexpected playing of The Ford-The Witch King and Nelya), and I lost against a moria swarm because I couldnt draw any minions at site 9.  I beat a Sauron discard deck, two Uruk decks, and another moria deck.  Against Sauron, protect against hate, and use sleep and athelas to rid conditions.  Against Uruks, move slowly and take wounds where you can, and let your minons do the work. Against Moria, save your sleep until they have 4 armories, swarms with lost of minons, TAC, and anything else they want to put down.  Most likely they wont be able to get them back, so you should be safe.  The deck basically relies on smart playing decisions and effective card usage to win.        <br>
<br>
To start the game, I usually bid 2 or 3.  If I can go 1st I usually do, but going 2nd is no problem.  Use the Pony to get Arogorn out, and play companions and stuff.  If you cant get the pony, dont worry because there are 8 companions in the deck and drawing one is usually no problem.  The deck usually cycles fairly well, and the fellowship usually sets up fairly slowly.  Again, the main focus on this deck is the shadow side.  Basically move whenever you can, and play the deck.  <br>
<br>
Card choices:<br>
<br>
Sites: The pony to get Mr. Gorn out, Ettenmoors to boost Uruks (Troops with Savagries and strength boosting can usaully kill early companions) Council Courtyard to remove 2, Hollin because it is the best Uruk site out there, The bridge because I couldnt decide what to use, Valley of the Silverlode to heal Frodo and Sam, Anduin Confluence to get rid of bounders, Elrond, or anyone else they have (my allies should already be used up so I dont care), Shores of Nen hithoel because if Im playing it, it means that they are ahead of me and I&#39;m using the high twilight.  Slopes because you can effectively create a mini Uruk swarm.<br>
<br>
Servant of the Secret Fire: The best skirmish event ever and a staple card in any Gandalf deck, IMHO.<br>
<br>
Gandalf Allies: i put Dreary in to rid those pesky Moria and Isengard conditions, and Butterbur because he&#39;s free and lets you re-use valuable sleep and badass Servant.<br>
<br>
Gandalf&#39;s gear: His staff is an awesome card and one of the most versatile cards in existance.  Vitality +1, spells -1, and skirmish canceler=way badass Gandalf.  Glamdring is a must for twilight removal and power.  Sleep Caradras?  Who doesnt use it in a Gandalf deck?<br>
<br>
Aragorn: because he is another badass and very useful at site 9 with an army of moria weaklings.  He can either shoot them down with his bow, or take them all on to save frodo.  His sword is in there for strength and damage, and he can use kingsfoil (Athelas) to rid conditions/wounds.  Flaming Brands for anti-nazgul and strength. <br>
<br>
Borimir: Borimir is one of my favorite companions.  he basically cant be overwhelmed with his sword and can wound minions with damage or exert to wound.  With armor he cant be stopped when fighting The Balrog or Cave Troll, etc.<br>
<br>
Gimili: basically for minion bait and perhaps to save frodo with his axe.  He is a very powerful companion on his own with his built-in buffer, and he can mean the difference between life and death when facing Moria swarm orcs.<br>
<br>
Arwen: Anti-nazgul and minion bait.  Plus the added cycling ability with Gwemegil is nice.  <br>
<br>
Legolas: Minion bait, but you can also use his bow to save frodo or kill stuff.  Just make sure he shoots stuff before you chump him.<br>
<br>
Sam: Burden removal and Balrog bait.  Maybe to carry on the ring if things get really bad...<br>
<br>
Frodo&#39;s Gear: Sting, Mithril-Coat and O Elbereth! are basically essentials for any deck.  They are just too good to not use.  PATHS is awesome and can mean the difference between a living Frodo and a dead one.  Just make sure you sleep their Armories before usage.<br>
<br>
<br>
Shadow:<br>
<br>
Troops: Anti strength is awesome.  Most of the people there used weapons for their fellowship, and these guys cancel it.  I killed this one guy&#39;s Frodo with a troop.  He had sting but the troop canceled it.  Is overwhelmtion a word?<br>
<br>
Uruk Scout: I hate ARV.  I like roaming -1.  I like the 3 twilight cost. <br>
<br>
Uruk Captain: Play Uruks from discard pile?  I&#39;m there!  And low twilight cost!<br>
<br>
Orthanc Assassin: Strength 10, Archer, dam +1, and vitality 3 all make this minion well worth the somewhat high twilight cost.<br>
<br>
Lurtz: Strength 13, Archer, dam +1, vitality 3, and possibly fierce.  A twilight of 7 is definately worth it!<br>
<br>
Ulaire Cantea: I like discarding weapons.  Add this with strength 10, fierce, and vitality 3 and you have one of the best minions in the game. <br>
<br>
Savegery:  The best Uruk card ever made.  I&#39;m sure every one of you reading this knows that.  Did I menion I have 4 of them now?  Yeah!<br>
<br>
Saruman&#39;s Ambition:  +2 strength and LBC and BTHOM at a -1 cost.  And it costs 0 to play.<br>
<br>
Bred For Battle:  Good strength booster and overwhelmer <br>
<br>
Lurtz&#39;s Battle Cry:  Plays for free with SA and kills companions.  Simple as that.<br>
<br>
Wizard&#39;s Storm.  Prevents from moving again.  If they do, then laugh silently as every one of their companions essentially takes a wound.  Almost always prevents fellowships from moving more than once a turn.  <br>
<br>
Beyond The Height of Men:  I hate armor and Gimili&#39;s Helm.  and with 2 SA&#39;s it plays for free.<br>
<br>
Spies of Saruman:  Skips one of the most deadly phases of the game to let your Uruks live another day.  <br>
<br>
The Balrog:  This is a no-brainer.  I killed numerous companions with him in the tourney, or at least caused massive damage.  Pullable for twilight cost of 6, fierce, dam +1, strength 17, vitality 5, and free spies of Saruman.  What better site 5 minion is there?<br>
<br>
<br>
I hope you enjoyed my long-winded and obnoxious strategy section.  Now go tell me whats wrong with the deck!  <br>
<br>
<br>
